{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599987"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:00:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:00:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15598"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15598"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.21,0.08,0,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70391"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8289"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55855"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70391"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with tremor, heat intolerance and weight loss. Thyroid function tests confirm hyperthyroidism. A thyroid biopsy shows hyperplastic follicular epithelial cells with scalloped colloid edges and lymphocytic infiltration.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hashimoto thyroiditis","Lymphocytic thyroiditis","Subacute granulomatous thyroiditis","Riedel thyroiditis","Graves disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological features described are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003EGraves disease\u003C/strong\u003E, showing hyperplastic follicular epithelial cells with scalloped colloid edges and lymphocytic infiltration. This pattern reflects the increased thyroid hormone production and autoimmune nature of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions show distinct histological patterns:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E shows extensive lymphoid infiltration with germinal centre formation and follicular destruction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphocytic thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E shows predominantly lymphocytic infiltration without marked follicular changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubacute granulomatous thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates granulomas with giant cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERiedel thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by dense fibrosis replacing normal thyroid tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features of hyperthyroidism along with the characteristic histological findings strongly support the diagnosis of Graves disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Graves disease shows characteristic histological features including hyperplastic follicular cells with scalloped colloid and lymphoid infiltrates","Thyroid histology can differentiate between various forms of thyroiditis based on cellular patterns and inflammatory infiltrates","Graves disease is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism in Australia"],"references":["\u0022Graves disease - alt -- high mag\u0022 by Librepath is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Graves_disease_-_alt_--_high_mag.jpg","Lane LC, Wood CL, Cheetham T. Graves\u0027 disease: moving forwards. Arch Dis Child. 2023 Apr;108(4):276-281. doi: 10.1136/archdischild-2022-323905. Epub 2022 Jul 13. PMID: 35831126; PMCID: PMC10086272","Girgis CM, Champion BL, Wall JR. Current concepts in graves\u0027 disease. Ther Adv Endocrinol Metab. 2011 Jun;2(3):135-44. doi: 10.1177/2042018811408488. PMID: 23148179; PMCID: PMC3474632","De Leo S, Lee SY, Braverman LE. Hyperthyroidism. Lancet. 2016 Aug 27;388(10047):906-918. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00278-6. Epub 2016 Mar 30. PMID: 27038492; PMCID: PMC5014602","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55855"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15598"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21170"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21170"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/clNaP5o9ClKyvKWkmuYstQwKDXAUBo.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/clNaP5o9ClKyvKWkmuYstQwKDXAUBo.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1000}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55855"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T20:21:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T20:29:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8289"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70391"}}},"meta":{"canDele